result.execSummary:
The defendant Nicholas E. Landon was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Costs shall be collected by the Department of Correction as a condition of Extended Supervision and/or Probation.
Defendant shall not possess or consume any nonprescription controlled substances, or any prescription medicine for which the defendant does not have a current prescription.
Defendant shall undergo an AODA assessment and follow through with all recommendations thereof.

records.addlTxt: Fax Confirmation to LCSO of JOC

2:53 PM / 3:08 PM
Defendant Nicholas E. Landon appeared by video and in custody.  Attorney Adam Thomas Witt appeared by video for Nicholas E. Landon.  Attorney Jenna L Gill in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Defendant waives his right to in person appearance for purposes of plea/sentencing today.
Attorney Witt Informs the court this matter is resolved the plea questionnaire and waiver of rights has been filed with the court.
Defendant enters plea of "NO CONTEST"- Both Counts .
Court questions defendant re: his plea and waiver of rights.
Court questions attorney Witt re: his clients plea and waiver of rights.
State waives right to jury trial.
Defendant is advised of their voting rights.
Court finds plea and waiver is made freely, voluntarily, and intelligently.
Court accepts plea and finds the defendant "GUILTY". 

Attorney Witt informs the court his client wishes to waive his right to preliminary hearing.
Court informs the defendant of his right to preliminary hearing and purpose of said hearing.
Court questions defendant re: his right to preliminary hearing.
Parties stipulate to a factual basis.
Court questions counsel re: his clients waiver of preliminary hearing.
Court finds waiver of preliminary is made freely, knowingly & voluntarily.
Court accepts waiver and orders bind over. 

State moves for joint recommendation of the parties.
Attorney Witt Joins in the motion.

Court Orders: Sentence Withheld Probation for a Period of 3 Years
-Costs
Return on warrant on October 4, 2022 at 02:30 pm.
